column188:
23/Oct/21 9:52 AM;Jaime_Gamez@raytheon.com;We won’t be signing up to earn backs because performing at or above the service levels is expected on an ongoing basis.  Also, we are already moving below what our service owners are expecting.

{color:#de350b}Not surprised.  We’ll remove it from the version we send back this afternoon.{color}

 

As for your service levels (Column H) changes, I don’t believe I can touch those given that is the underlying level that our service owners expect.  What are the specific issues with these driving these changes?

{color:#de350b}98% on resolution, particularly for lower priorities seems punitive.  The scenario would be that if we resolved 29 out of 30 P2 or P3 on time, we would still get penalized.    90 or 95 is more standard{color}

 

As for +60 days for Service Level Credit Effective Date (Column J), are you saying that this would be credited 60 days in areas of incident.  Why wouldn’t this be 30 days?

{color:#de350b}No.  The concept here is that we start measuring and reporting service levels on the service level effective date (Column I), but the service level credits starts 2 months later.   This allows us to make sure that we are measuring appropriately and it allows us to make any adjustments required to achieve the service levels.{color}

 

Removing the weighting enhancements (Column P) would have to be reviewed.

{color:#de350b}This is very important to us.   It seems to be very punitive and greatly increases the risk of a single event driving penalties to the cap.{color}

 

I’m willing to lower some of the penalty percentages of the Priority 3s but that would be all I can likely do.

{color:#de350b}I think we are getting close, but anything you can do would help.{color};;;

